 1. Java Introduction
Java is a high-level, object-oriented, platform-independent programming language.
Follows WORA: Write Once, Run Anywhere.
Used in web apps, mobile apps (Android), desktop apps, games, etc.

2. Comments in Java
Single-line: // This is a single-line comment

Multi-line :
/* This is
   a multi-line comment */

3. Literals
Constants used directly in code.

Examples:
Integer: 10
Float: 3.14f
Char: 'A'
String: "Hello"
Boolean: true, false

4. Identifiers
Names for variables, classes, methods.
Rules:
Start with a letter, _, or $.
No keywords allowed.
Case-sensitive.

5. Data Types
➤ Primitive types (8 total):
Integer: byte, short, int, long
Floating point: float, double
Character: char
Boolean: boolean

➤ Non-Primitive types:
String, Arrays, Classes, Interfaces, etc.

6. Variables
Containers for storing data.
Declaration: int age = 25;

7. Constants
Fixed values, cannot be changed after assignment.

Use final keyword: final double PI = 3.14159;

8. Keywords
There are 53 Reserved words with special meaning.
Examples: int, class, if, else, for, return, static, final, etc.

9. Operators and Types
➤ Arithmetic: +, -, *, /, %
➤ Relational: ==, !=, >, <, >=, <=
➤ Logical: &&, ||, !
➤ Assignment: =, +=, -=, etc.
➤ Unary: ++, --, +, -, !
➤ Ternary: condition ? true_value : false_value
➤ Bitwise: &, |, ^, ~, <<, >>

10. if, if-else, else-if Statements
if (condition) {
    // code
} else if (anotherCondition) {
    // code
} else {
    // code
}

11. switch Statement
switch (expression) {
    case value1:
        // code
        break;
    case value2:
        // code
        break;
    default:
        // code
}
